1. In SQL, this would be done using a series of joins across tables like drivers, trips, companies, and areas. You would connect drivers to trips using a driver ID then link trips to companies and areas through their respective keys. The query would basically chain these joins together to follow the same path as the graph traversal. You could also use GROUP BY if you need counts or summaries. It ends up being more manual since every step in the relationship has to be explicitly written out.
2. In Neo4j, nodes are directly connected through relationships so the database can just follow those links step by step. There is no need to repeatedly match keys or look things up through indexes at each step. This makes multihop queries feel more natural since you are just walking through the graph. In a relational database, each hop turns into another join which adds overhead and slows things down as the query gets more complex.
3. Neo4j can struggle when the task is more about scanning and aggregating large amounts of data instead of following relationships. Something like calculating average fare or total trips across the dataset is usually faster in a relational system. SQL databases are built to handle those kinds of operations efficiently especially when they can use optimized query plans and indexing.
